

<worksheet xml:id="A08_Units-and-Dimensions">
  <title>Math 150  Activity 08: Units and Dimensions</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A joule (<quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="joule"/></quantity>) is an amount of energy.
        A watt is a rate at
        which energy is used, defined to be
        <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="joule"/><per base="second"/></quantity>.
      </p>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          How many joules of energy are required to run a
          <quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="watt"/></quantity>
          light bulb for one day?
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          Burning coal yields about
          <quantity><mag>30d6</mag><unit base="joule"/></quantity>
          of energy
          per kilogram of coal burned.
          Assuming that a coal power plant is
          30<percent /> efficient, how much coal has to be burned to light the bulb
          for a day?
        </p>
      </task>

      <p>
        Growing Corn
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume that sunlight deposits energy on a cornfield at the rate
        of
        <quantity><mag>250</mag><unit base="watt"/><per base="meter" exp="2"/></quantity>,
        averaging over the day-night cycle.
        There are
        <quantity><mag>4.186</mag><unit base="joule"/></quantity>
        in a calorie.
      </p>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          How much energy
          (in calories)
          is deposited on a square meter
          of field over the 4-month growing season?
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          In good growing conditions, farmers can grow approximately
          12500 ears of sweet corn per acre.
          Use this to estimate the amount
          of sunlight energy per ear of corn.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          Nutrition labels for corn indicate that there are roughly 120
          calories in an ear of corn.
          The word <q>calories</q>, when you see it
          on a food label, actually means <q>kilocalories</q>.
          That is, the 120
          labeled calories corresponds to 120,000 true calories,
          or 120 kcal.
          Compare sunlight energy with the corn energy to get an efficiency in
          percent.
        </p>
      </task>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <p>
    Building Hoover Dam
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The Hoover Dam produces
        <quantity><mag>2d9</mag><unit base="watt"/></quantity>
        of electricity
        energy.
        It is composed of
        <quantity><mag>7d9</mag><unit prefix="kilo" base="gram"/></quantity>
        of concrete.
        To
        produce
        <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit prefix="kilo" base="gram"/></quantity>
        of concrete requires
        <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit prefix="mega" base="joule"/></quantity>
        of energy.
      </p>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          How much energy did it take to produce the concrete in the dam?
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          How long is the <q>energy payback time</q> for the dam? (Give
          your answer in years.)
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          The area of Lake Mead, formed by Hoover Dam, is <m>247\;\mathrm{
          mi}^2</m>.
          Assuming that
          <quantity><mag>250</mag><unit base="watt"/><per base="meter" exp="2"/></quantity>
          of sunlight energy (on
          average) falls on Lake Mead,
          how much power could you produce if instead of the lake you installed solar cells with 12<percent /> efficiency?
          Give your answer in Watts.
        </p>
      </task>

      <p>
        Dimensional Analysis
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If we don't want to specify units,
        we can still talk about the
        <em>dimensions</em> of quantities.
        Dimensions are things like length <m>L</m>,
        time <m>T</m>,
        temperature <m>\theta</m>, mass <m>M</m>, and so on.
        We use [square brackets]
        to indicate the dimension of a unit:
        for example, the dimension of meter is
        length, or <m>[\lt quantity>\lt unit base="meter"/>\lt /quantity>] = L</m>.
      </p>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          A joule is defined to be
          <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="joule"/></quantity>
          =
          <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="meter" exp="2"/><unit base="meter" exp="2"/><per base="second" exp="2"/></quantity>.
          What is the dimension of this quantity?
          Express your answer as a <em>product of
          integer powers</em> of the dimensions given above.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          What is the dimension of the energy delivery unit
          <quantity><unit base="watt"/><per base="meter" exp="2"/></quantity>
          that appears in the previous problems?
        </p>
      </task>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>

